-- Contraposition
--
-- STATUS: CONCEPTUAL (Issue #148)
-- This file EXPLAINS how contraposition works in CredTT but the `by negate`
-- tactic does NOT exist. Negation stability flipping is a DESIGN CONCEPT
-- documented here; no implementation verifies it.
--
-- Classical: (A -> B) <-> (~B -> ~A)
-- CredTT: Stability-contraposition (not exact equivalence!)
--         Stable(A -> B) implies bound on ~B -> ~A
--
-- Example: If rain -> wet ground, then dry ground -> no rain
-- Classical: Exact equivalence
-- CredTT: Credence and stability transform under negation

-- Classical contraposition is EXACT: A->B iff ~B->~A
-- CredTT contraposition is APPROXIMATE: stability bounds

-- Original implication at credence c
postulate rain_implies_wet : rain_to_wet @ c

-- Contraposition in CredTT:
-- If A -> B @ c, what is ~B -> ~A?
--
-- NOT exact equivalence! Negation FLIPS stability:
-- Stable1 -> Unstable0
-- Unstable0 -> Stable1
--
-- So contraposition relates STABILITY, not just truth

-- Stable implication
postulate stable_impl : A_implies_B @ 1
stable stable_impl

-- Negation flips stability: credence 1 becomes 1-1=0
-- The negated claim has VANISHING credence (stability flipped)
derive neg_B_implies_neg_A : not_B_to_not_A @ 0 from stable_impl by negate

-- The negated implication has flipped stability!
-- If original was Stable1, negation is Unstable0
-- This is HONEST: negation changes the character of the claim

-- Classical contraposition hides this stability flip
-- CredTT exposes it: you can't freely negate without consequence

-- Example of why this matters:
-- "If P then Q" @ 0.9 (pretty confident)
-- "If not Q then not P" @ 0.9 (same credence)
-- BUT: the STABILITY changed!
-- Near-1 confidence in P->Q doesn't mean near-1 confidence in ~Q->~P
-- It means the NEGATED claim has different sensitivity to perturbation
